               <history>
                  <origin><origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1684">1096 AH (1684
                        CE)</origDate></origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently owned or inspected by at least four individuals, 3 of
                        whom left namesake seal impressions on folios <locus from="1a" to="1b">1a
                           and 1b</locus> dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1693" to="1693"
                           >1105 AH (1693–94 AH)</date> and another of <persName role="seal">Sayyid
                           Abū al-Fatḥ Mustaqīm</persName>, dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                           from="1761" to="1762">1175 AH (1761–62 AH)</date>, as well as ownership
                        notes by <persName role="ato ins fmo">Ḥajjī Muhammad Ṣarrāf
                           Iṣfahānī</persName> and his son <persName role="ato fmo ins">Muḥammad
                           Ṭālib</persName> on folios <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> and the
                        latter again on <locus from="402b" to="402b">402b</locus>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Later acquired by by <persName type="standard" role="fmo ato seal"
                           key="person_f6703">Edward Galley (ca. 1750–1804)</persName>, <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/239176400">East India Company</orgName>
                        Resident at <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7018005"
                           key="place_7018005">Bushire (Bushehr)</placeName> between <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" from="1780" to="1787">1780 to 1787</date>, where he
                        probably obtained this volume. Ultimately Lieutentant-Governor of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001592" key="place_7001592"
                           >Surat</placeName> where he passed away, after his death, Galley's family
                        sold a portion of his library in Surat including volumes obtained by David
                        Price (see Robinson, p. 209). However, they evidently returned to Britain
                        and subsequently sold the remainder through the <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName> firm of
                           <persName role="auc" key="person_10201461">Samuel Leigh
                           Sotheby</persName> on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1837-06-30">30
                           June 1837</date>, lot 237.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Probably acquired at Galley's sale by <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName>
                        bookseller <persName role="bsl" cert="high"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/12688740" key="person_12688740">Henry George
                           Bohn (1796–1884)</persName>, who then offered it for sale in his <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1841">1841</date> catalogue, no. 13638,
                        described in the present binding for 2£ 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi> 6<hi
                           rend="italic">d</hi>. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Probably purchased from Bohn by orientalist <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/" key="person_66617580" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Duncan Forbes (1798–1868)</persName>.
                        Ultimately appointed <orgName>King's College</orgName> Professor of Oriental
                        Languages, Forbes described this volume in his <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1866">1866</date> catalogue, valued at £6 16<hi rend="italic"
                           >s</hi> and 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>
                        <!-- (also inscribed on the <locus
                           from="Inner_front_cover" to="Inner_front_cover">right pastedown</locus>) -->,
                        before he sold his manuscript collection to his publisher <orgName
                           role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747" key="person_152259747"
                              ><persName key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl"
                              change="#prov-markup">W. H. Allen </persName>&amp; Co.</orgName> in
                        exchange for an annuity.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently sold by <orgName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747" key="person_152259747"><persName
                              key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl" change="#prov-markup">W.
                              H. Allen </persName>&amp; Co.</orgName> to <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date> for his Bibliotheca Lindesiana at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
